post_text:
A special message from Superintendent Holtom.
Next Wednesday, July 1, The Oroville City Elementary School District will be sharing publicly our comprehensive plan regarding the reopening of schools in August. I want to reassure parents that we will be offering multiple programs for students and their families, including a traditional 5 day a week program following our regular bell schedule, in addition to an enhanced distance learning program that was similar to the one we had in the spring. I know you have numerous questions and we are working very hard to provide a lot of answers as part of our July 1 press release. Following that July 1 press release we will be surveying families again to help us better prepare for the reopening of schools.
text:

I know you have numerous questions and we are working very hard to provide a lot of answers as part of our July 1 press release. Following that July 1 press release we will be surveying families again to help us better prepare for the reopening of schools.

post_text:
Notice: Mesa Avenue Closure
Mesa Avenue once past the gate for Central Middle School is the property of Oroville City Elementary School District and is not a public road.
In an effort to increase the safety of staff, students and their families, Oroville City Elementary School District will be permanently closing Mesa Avenue to non-school related traffic using gates and barriers.
For students and families of Central Middle School and Sierra Del Oro Preschool, more information will be sent to you prior to the beginning of the 2020-21 school year.
If you have any questions about this change, please contact the district office via email at backpack@ocesd.net.

Oroville City Elementary is working on plans to return to school for the 2020-21 school year. Watch our website or social media for updates.

post_text:
In case you missed the phone call this morning, here is what it said: Good morning Oroville City Elementary School District families,
This is Spencer Holtom, Superintendent with a very import announcement. Due to the President's recommendation and orders to continue social distancing and not gather in groups of ten or more the Oroville City Elementary School District, will continue providing alternative learning until May 1st, 2020. While these are unprecedented times the entire staff here in Oroville are here to serve you. Please continue to reach out teachers, site administrators or the district office if you have any questions. Please stay healthy and have a great day.

post_text:
Blood Donation Event
Jun 6 from 1:00 PM to 5:00 PM
Oroville Sports Club, 2600 Oro Dam Blvd E, Oroville, CA 95966, USA
Come donate blood In support of Joshua Glaum, Wyandotte Academy student. Joshua was recently diagnosed with AML (acute melanoid leukemia) and is undergoing extremely aggressive treatments. Joshua and Northern California blood banks are in need of type O blood. BloodSource asks that we RSVP so that they can staff this event appropriately. Mention that you are part of the Joshua Glaum Donor's Club!

post_text: At 10:10 a.m., Stanford School went into lockdown due to loud noises heard by the playground. At 10:20, Ishi MS also went into lockdown. OPD responded. Investigation revealed that a piece of equipment at a neighboring house had exploded. The lockdown was lifted at 10:37 a.m.
